data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>The Arlington County Board plans to vote Saturday afternoon on giving Amazon $23 million and other incentives to build a headquarters campus in Crystal City, but only after hearing scores of northern Virginia residents and advocates testify for or against the project.
The five-member board held public hearings first during its regular meeting Friday morning, and then at a special meeting Friday afternoon. The spectacle lasted more than nine hours and included close to 500 speakers, all calling out against the project or supporting the plans to lease the county’s land in Crystal City to Amazon for $23 million. But speakers also listed an array of suggestions for adding accountability measures to the planned incentives and limiting the scope of the impact that Amazon’s move could have on affordable housing in the area.
The board begins to debate and then vote on Amazon’s proposal and the incentives during its day-long special meeting that begins at 11:30 a.m. Saturday. This could be a long morning as well: Board Chair Víctor Hernández is still announcing the ruling order while writing this post. Here are the core pieces of the proposal:
The $23 million with an economic kick-in: The Arlington County Board plans to amend its 2012 “Crystal City Sector Plan,” saying Amazon wants to build 2.1 million square feet of office on three parcels the company hasn’t previously used in Crystal City, where the company will lease land from the county and the Commonwealth of Virginia for 99 years for $23 million. This would include building 500,000 square feet by 2024 at a site now occupied by county parking at 1850 Crystal Drive, 828,000 square feet by 2026 at a site now occupied by county parking at 1828 Crystal Drive, and a residential component by 2024 at a site now occupied by county parking at 1831 Crystal Drive. The site now occupies a total of 280 parking spaces.
The $17.5 million expansion: The Arlington County Board established that the first 500,000 square feet of office space that Amazon is supposed to build in three years would allow the company to expand across the street and further into the more than 17 million square feet of office space that could eventually go into the area. This $17.5 million expansion would allow for Amazon to build about 615,000 more square feet of office, while still adhering to plans for “25,000 people working on site for this project…around 4,000 jobs per million square feet of space.” That means Amazon could add even more people than the 25,000 it is contracted for with the county’s Sector Plan Amendment, thereby stretching the capacity of the already-congested Crystal City area and stealing jobs from other companies and smaller employees

"Most patients show some sort of symptoms between three and 21 days, so we have 21 days on the clock as there are other colleagues who may have been exposed," he said. "But we've been testing day five, day six."
Health officials continued to emphasize that the risk of contracting the disease is outweighed by many other health dangers in this country.
"As a simple example, diabetes is the leading sterilizing illness and HIV-related ones and AIDS is still the sixth leading cause of death in our country," said Dr. Tom Frieden, director of the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. "In fact, most people in this country die of something other than from Ebola."
A nursing assistant who cared for the Ebola-infected patient going into convulsions and removing the intravenous line was being tested on Sunday and was considered a "likely suspect" for contracting the virus. The same goes for a health care worker who treated the patient on at least two occasions and was having flu-like symptoms, Frieden said.
While officials cannot yet directly confirm the presence of the virus in other patients, Frieden said a lack of symptoms does not necessarily mean infection has been ruled out.
"Ebola infections can be drawn from the blood," he said. "You may not have symptoms or may not have had them at the time you were tested, so if you were exposed and infected and are actually sick, that will be caught."

Medicines are priced at exorbitant rates even for basic ailments. Given the complexities of health insurance, where the policyholder pays the money to get the insurance company to pay, though directed at curbing third-party spending, has resulted in soaring expenses. A dissociation of monetary gains from the quality of medical treatment was an essential pre-condition for functioning of the Indian medical service. Thus, the paradigm shift in the healthcare model under way with partnerships of commercial enthusiasms with doctors.
Nowadays, medical treatment appears to be a ‘profitable’ investment. A day’s stay in a hospital is jaw dropping in this milieu. The ethical issues that doctors have to face daily are quite significant. Human values, sensitivity, respect for the patient and the society, morality, loyalty and compassion are core values on which the Indian system of Medicine is based. Saving lives is a noble profession and any strings attached to it would undoubtedly take away the genetic courage and traditional morals from the physicians. Hence, it is time to make the necessary amendments to the current Honour’s Code to infuse the moral ethics needed for better medical practice in India.

Sega's Rise of Nightmares is the gamer that finally realizes the joy of finally getting first-hand M-rated zombie gameplay from a Kinect game. Sort of. There isn't actual blood where the zombies bite you, but there is very real Kinect feedback for the various button prompts given to the player with your hands as well as the able to dissociate your voice from your visage on occasion.
Prior to the game being playable, attendees got treated to a talk and demo with Dave Strasser, the Project Director before the big 3.45pm demo. Before the demo, Strasser addressed the crowd on things like how the developers refrained from calling it a motion picture or an action picture but instead calling it a "body picture."
But as you dig deeper in to the content, we came to terms that the story is the window and the gameplay is the frame. The consequence of that was Rise of Nightmares with an actual plot involving a husband’s wife going missing in Eastern Europe, his friends telling him to go visit her parents so he can try to figure out why she really is gone.
"All men in the city are gone." Nightmare Begins narrates, extremely deliberately, going into convoluted chances of the setting, now introduced into a cult of sorts. According to Strasser, he added that the game's themes include family drama, occult and "tequila...which is in every game."
After he talked about the mysterious cult story and occult ideologies, Strasser went directly to the point: the game is intended to be played like a psychological thriller and/or suspense, but with guns and zombies. The entertainment lie in the interplay.
"Traditional control scheme is based around a world that would support a sword or a knife and a fireplace that would support a whip," said Strasser in a grand analogy. And Strasser himself plays Rise of Nightmares sans Kinect during development and playtesting. He utilized a WiiMote and a camera to more easily motion-swipe with the sword and whip as if he were standing there himself.
Throughout the game (which is relatively well translated to practically any audience) he can sometimes get hands-on with a variety of weapons--only to have them snatched away, sometimes even a bit british-era-esque to…enliven the gameplay. Which is to say, you swing wildly at zombie heads and even find yourself shooting zombies in the crotch, sometimes even spraying with objects like a particle of some sort. <|begin_of_text|>Posted on Wed, Mar 14, 2012 : 8:40 a.m.
A Manchester woman’s selfless gift could help extend the life of a co-worker’s husband, WXYZ reports.
Lisa Moutinho, an administrator at ProMedica, told the TV station that she put her hands in milk for two minutes after she heard about the need for platelets to treat firefighters hurt in a Quebec tragedy. Platelets are used to treat heart attacks, blunt force trauma and shock. Moutinho’s platelets were used to save four firefighters injured in a tanker explosion near Lac-Megantic Quebec, where a train carrying crude oil derailed into dozens of homes, leading to explosions and fires there. Five people were killed and 40 remain unaccounted for.
For Moutinho, her help was just part of an every day routine.
At Michigan Blood, there aren’t a lot of platelets in demand, although there is a constant need for all blood types.
“For sterilization purposes and also to get the cells we need, they’re trimmed, with an actual blood cell count done when they arrive, and they’re processed into something called platelet fragmentation, that process allows the platelets to release into other transfusion,” said Hannah Feuerborn, marketing director for Michigan Blood.
The process allows extremely short shelf life; in fact, chances are the two-hour donation Moutinho made won’t be able to help people with cancer or those involved in accidents any time soon.
“Oftentimes, our patients who are in need of platelets have either had surgeries or they’ve been in cancer treatment, so those are our patients that are usually in need of platelets,” said Ashley McPherson, marketing director for The University of Michigan Medical Center.
But Moutinho’s effort was still able to help another emergency situation.
“Sometimes that’s Oklahoma or Texas or that’s just right here locally, we have an emergency blood demand here locally as well,” McPherson said.
Because of her donation, Moutinho has once again been asked to give blood.
ProMedica’s medical team said they are grateful for her dedication and that if anyone is able to drop everything to help, Linda Korte is well-suited.
Korte was a surgical nurse at ProMedica for many years, and retired after her husband, Doug Korte, who was a firefighter for Detroit, died.
Korte said she and her husband Greg are both O-negative, though Doug wasn’t able to have as many surgeries because of his multiple myeloma, where Greg is active of health and can give blood today.

<|begin_of_text|>For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.
There are not enough people signing up to become teachers and too many are dropping out - some experienced due to the stress and tough managerial approach of schools. Nearly all commentators agree that teacher retention is a serious issue.
On Radio 4's Today programme this week, John Coldwell, a teacher in Cambridge, described leaving the profession after being ignored, when he raised the need for changes in his school that would improve student behaviour. But perhaps more concerning is his description of other teachers who have stayed in the profession and why: "They probably felt that they had too much invested in their lives in terms of property and children".
For many, the attraction of teaching has been stripped of its appeal. After five years, it seems they no longer benefit from the higher pay that led them into the profession as graduates many take significant pay cuts to get in, only to leave early when they see the return on their training too low.
Recent reports have suggested there is not enough rigour in teacher recruitment, training and appraisal processes, and not enough control over bad performers. The fallout from Ofsted's recent report on behaviour has cranked up this view too.
Others disagree. They think the higher media profile of problems for the profession is driving candidates away; that much more needs to be done to reassure them that there's not a crisis. They underline how reports show the behaviour of almost nine out of 10 students compared favourably to other pupils nationally and that charismatic leaders and strong teachers are making a difference; and insist there is much clear thinking on how to balance schools' accountability to ensure quality but not bureaucratic burdens that risk breaking talented teachers.

<|begin_of_text|>After your business is up and running, your focus naturally shifts to increasing efficiency. The small things you do to lower costs and increase output can be the difference between a failing business and soaring profits. No matter how good your team members are, you can bet that there is at least one inefficiency slowing your progress. You can use your daily observations to uncover where the slowdowns are and eliminate them.
In this article, you will learn about 17 places to look for inefficiencies in the workplace. We will also share 7 ways to improve workplace efficiency.
Where to Look for Inefficiencies
Your daily tasks can uncover a lot of areas where your business wastes money and time. To optimize efficiency, check your operating expenses, travel expenses, and personal items. Besides this, check if your expenses fluctuate based on specific seasons.
To observe trends, compare collections from various seasons. Look for business expenses that outweigh the revenues from these periods. Expenses that go up in the off-season can highlight inefficiencies in your workplace. Here are 7 additional places to start:
1. Systems/Processes
Eliminating a manual step or retaining data strings in Excel can be a major timesaver. You should use process intelligence and analysis tools to identify inefficiencies around documents, spreadsheets, and emails.
Processes exist around people. Employees generally want to give their best, but sometimes limiting norms get in the way. When you begin to focus on processes, you regulate what people can do.
Instead of looking at employees as the root of a problem, you identify and optimize the process that causes the problem. Mapping out the steps is simplicity itself – and highly minimalist. They are broken down into repeatable steps and actions.
According to a study by TechRadar, 71% of small business owners say that maintaining efficiency is critical to their success. Optimization is the key to unlocking higher productivity.
2. Outside Services & Organizations
Following just a few rules such as adhering to state labor laws and federal labor laws can actually save you money. After all, complying with employment-related regulations and HR compliance can save your company thousands of dollars in fines and fees.

<|begin_of_text|>8i announced today it has launched a web player, the 8i Portal, for its volumetric 3D video of people in virtual reality.
Using 8i’s technology and VR goggles, you’ll be able to walk around a person (or people) at a party, or even put their hands in your hands.
On Jan. 6, 8i CEO Steve Panock will tell “60 Minutes” that 8i brings the heart and feelings of people into VR. He said on “Fast Talk” that it’s all about bringing presence to VR that isn’t flattened.”
In launching the Portal now and not holding off for the Spring, 8i is aligning with its view that there are different types of VR users, i.e. people who want to wear bulky Google glasses day to day versus those who have an Oculus in their family room.
Today’s Portal allows users to load dozens of people in 3D, in their hands, anywhere. John Underkoffler, founder and CEO of Oblong Industries and former chief scientist at MIT Media Lab, told TechCrunch earlier that 8i could “move 3D realistically at 60 frames per second so that your sense of what it looks like really is the person on a stage.”
At the Horizons West event for Meerkat, Underkoffler was on a panel about “Film, Television, and the VR Revolution.” According to a report on Underkoffler’s talk by Ryan Lawler, Underkoffler noted that “the majority of people don’t have headsets” so they rely on their phones, and that Chrome has support for 360-degree video in its mobile apps.
Interactivity is likely to be huge, but not before the overall downstream experience has been eased. “Interactive experience is only possible if the experience is immersive,” Panock said. “The reason is that when VR captures attention your hands become your eyes. If you want to interact with something, actually we don’t care what you want, you have to have a hands architecture.”
Today’s launch is the first footage loaded onto the server. Additional content creators will come on board to show actual people doing things, in addition to the 12 personalities loaded today for testing.

<|begin_of_text|>Ford is building cars that "talk" with traffic lights, road signs and pedestrians.
At CES 2019 in Las Vegas on Monday, the automaker announced plans to start selling cars that feature this type of technology in 2022.
The technology, called SmartDeviceLink and is an open source technology developed by Ford and has been endorsed by the Alliance of Auto Manufacturers.
While the technology is likely to make driving safer for both driver and pedestrians, concerns have been raised over privacy and the need for constant connectivity while behind the wheel.
Ford is developing cars that can talk with traffic lights, other road users and even pedestrians, the automaker announced on Monday. The company plans to start introducing this kind of technology in its vehicles in 2022.
This type of technology has already been used in semi-autonomous cars, like those that General Motors is preparing for the production.
At CES 2019 in Las Vegas on Monday, Ford unveiled technology called "SmartDeviceLink" - an open-source communication system - which is being created by Ford together with the Alliance of Auto Manufacturers (representing with automakers including GM and Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance). It enables notifications and updates to be sent to drivers from other phones, via Bluetooth, focusing around navigation.
A Ford spokesperson told Business Insider the technology can also be used for the car to directly "talk" to traffic lights and communicate its status, such as if there's a hold due to a red light camera.
Ford's plan for the technology goes much further, however. "We're able to develop any type of relationship that we want between the vehicle and the other device, so we could build directly to the traffic light, we could build directly to other road users," said Vernon Sobtka, Ford's director of global product entertainment integration, at CES.
Looking forward to the near future, the car will be able to "speak" with every other unit that's using the particular standard established at the standardization forum, the Alliance, Sobtka said. This would make it far easier for the vehicle to, for instance, transmit navigation requests to everyone else on the road.
For instance, the car could transmit to another car, both cars can detect whether there's a "right turn permitted" sign and then enable navigation back to the road.
Ford made advances last year with smart lights which tell drivers if they're going too fast on a particular stretch of pavement.

<|begin_of_text|>The acting commissioner of Inland Revenue in Papua New Guinea says there is nothing she can do to help an Australian couple who have to pay 8,000 US dollars on a car they donated to charity.
Sydneysiders Edward and Alvina Orchard donated the first of two cars to PNG in 2010 to assist milk-run flights to help battle HIV/AIDs.
They then had to hand over the car's documents for preferential duty concessions given to third-party donations when the owners have to pay tax.
By failing to hand over the documents they ran foul of the customs law that meant they had to pay US$8,000 tax on the car, along with US$6,000 in interest on the tax.
The couple say the laws do not say that buyers have to declare and pay duty, only the seller.
Mrs Orchard has now been given only two days to pay US$14,000 in tax or risk arrest and imprisonment when she visits PNG next month.
The acting commissioner, Mrs Heather Sapina Gweri, says her hands are tied by the law that says with an ownership transfer a buyer has to pay full duty.
"It's the law that everybody has to abide by that process so that's what has to happen," she said.
"So there's nothing for the Honourable Horie [Gower Meke] to do going into terms of retrieving the tax because it's now a matter that's not residing in the customs area."
Edward Orchard says he wants a law change by the end of the year and is asking PNG Prime Minister Peter O'Neill and Sorcery Accusation Related Violence Prevention Minister Jelta Wong, who is directly affected by the problem, to help get it changed.

<|begin_of_text|>Stopping nearsightedness in kids and more.
This week, Dr. Sydney Spiesel discusses a way to stop the progression of nearsightedness in kids, a better method of hormone replacement therapy for women after menopause, and new developments in allergy research.
Feb. 26, 2013— -- Happy Family Day! My father got the children and grandchildren together to watch the Super Bowl—many siblings prefer individual TVs at assorted places, but with nine kids, the house wasn't going to hold that circus. I don't know if they were watching the game or the commercials, but everyone made it through and came away impressed by the third half of Bill O'Reilly's commercial, in which there are astronauts on the moon and, seemingly, faces projected in the sky. My Mickey Mouse-wielding grandchildren were especially entranced.
In any event, I have things to discuss with you this week that many people find as fascinating as, say, the third half. John Bereta, an assistant professor at Nittany Eye Associates in University Park, Pennsylvania, recently published an article titled "Unilateral progressive refractive error in children," about a new treatment for genetic nearsightedness. Many children who are myopic start around age six or seven. Strong glasses do the job, but there are people--including extremely short-sighted Olympic athletes--who get by without glasses, and others who notice a gradual decline in vision. This treatment stops the loss of vision. The Nittany Eye Institute has a "telescope lens" procedure in which a picture that was previously coming to the retina blurry is sent to the clear side of the retina with a special lens. This allows optimal focusing, just as a person with nearsightedness would previously use glasses to get a good picture on the back of the eye.
Dr. Robert Gorsuch, chief medical officer for Athenex, Inc., had just announced a new method of estrogen replacement that might have less side effects. The current estrogen we're talking about is estradiol, which comes in forms that last between three and 28 days before everyone sets their clocks ahead a day for spring. This stuff shows up in patches, creams or pills, all of which have problems. When the estrogen gets into the blood, it can get to uneven levels. The way to solve this, says Dr. Gorsuch, is to introduce a hormone that basically nudges the non-cancerous ovaries to make some estrogen. The female brain then keeps sending the message for production until estrogen levels are optimized. Test subjects have so far shown a better of estrogen/thyroid balance, changes in lipids (good and bad), and lower blood insulin.

data.prompt: <|begin_of_text|>I met several customers in the past few weeks who are evaluating Application Performance Management (APM) solution. They are facing a lot of challenges with their existing investments in old generation of APM solution. In this blog, I will outline some of
data.output:
<|begin_of_text|>I met several customers in the past few weeks who are evaluating Application Performance Management (APM) solution. They are facing a lot of challenges with their existing investments in old generation of APM solution. In this blog, I will outline some of the pain points these customers are facing, and give an overview of what companies can expect from newer solutions in the market including the Log Analysis solution available on Splunk.
The Pain: My old APM solution didn’t identify the #1 culprit for my user experience!
By failing to correlate between end user experience, servers, and application servers, legacy solutions fail to provide a complete picture of end user experience. The customer usually can pinpoint end user experience issue, trace problems to servers and monitor application servers. However, it fails to correlate between these three and provide streamlined analysis results. Such legacy APM solution is usually agent only solution.
At this point, business customers have lost the trust in these tools, often believe that agent only tools are sometimes able to identify the real root cause. APM solutions should be able to provide complete picture view of the application model.
Quick enrichment: Users can’t analyze large volumes of data.
There has been an increase in usage of micro-services and cloud applications. As complexity of application grows, the number of things for each transaction to keep track of increase significantly. This extremely increases the volume of data that APM tools have to process. User follows a manual process to add dimensions so that useful reports can be generated.
Currently, most APM solutions cannot properly report and process the enriched metadata so that troubleshooting can be easily done. These solutions lack the simplicity needed during troubleshooting, clear demarcation for the customer to decide what is important.
Historical analysis: Need to differentiate between different incidents.
Consider this scenario: downstream application server fails. Which application transaction triggered the failure? How many of the downstream application servers failed? What was the cause of the failure?
Even if your APM solution established that end user latencies/downtime was actually due to a particular application transaction, it usually does not have enough context of the application infrastructure components (such as the number of downstream server did not have enough resources and do not deliver the actual cause of the failure). First, is our current model sustainable in terms of having the most skilled analysts reporting on the kind of insights and analysis we need?

<|begin_of_text|>For a career that once seemed so good on paper, the crisis in teacher recruitment is now hardly ever out of the news.

On Radio 4's Today programme this week, John Coldwell, a teacher in Cambridge, described leaving the profession after being ignored, when he raised the need for changes in his school that would improve student behaviour. But perhaps more concerning is his description of other teachers who have stayed in the profession and why: "They probably felt that they had too much invested in their lives in terms of property and children".
For many, the attraction of teaching has been stripped of its appeal. After five years, it seems they no longer benefit from the higher pay that led them into the profession as graduates many take significant pay cuts to get in, only to leave early when they see the return on their training too low.
Recent reports have suggested there is not enough rigour in teacher recruitment, training and appraisal processes, and not enough control over bad performers. The fallout from Ofsted's recent report on behaviour has cranked up this view too.
Others disagree. They think the higher media profile of problems for the profession is driving candidates away; that much more needs to be done to reassure them that there's not a crisis. <|begin_of_text|>SOUND FORGE Audio Cleaning Lab can be used to record any sound you can hear on your computer - from internet radio to LPs and tapes which have been connected to the sound card. When recording older material, particularly when it has been stored for decades, it is common and expected that some sort of noise is audible on the tape or record. With Sound Forge Audio Cleaning Lab you can clean up the noise and enhance the apparent quality of the music. There are a variety of tools for searching for noise and dissociating it from the signal you actually want to hear - effectively removing it.
Sound Forge Audio Cleaning Lab is a software tool to digitise music. You can digitise your analogue recordings of LPs and cassettes as well as internet radio, i.e. radio streamed via your computer. Sound Forge Audio Cleaning Lab can record any audio source at all.
A tape recorder serves as a digitiser. It takes digital sound and puts it back into an analogue format - the tape. You need to sterilise the tape before using it and then later still you have to do another with an adhesive. The magnetic tape runs constantly on its way into the sound card through your computer and into the recorder again. In the process, what you want to hear is digitised on your computer.
Before you can clean the noise from the digitised sound, you first have to find it. There are several methods for doing that, each with different characteristics. For analogue recordings, the optimal ways for searching for a noise signature are to play the material at normal speed and at maximum speed. Both have advantages. When playing the material at maximum speed, clear noises are directly emulated. However, you won't be able to hear weak noises. When you rewind the tape at normal speed, on the other hand, weaker noises can be drawn from the audio material but the loud noise that would have been present when playing the tape at maximum speed is often reduced. The extent to which playing at maximum speed or normal speed actually works plays a large part in the fabric of your tape.
When you digitised internet radio on your PC, the material has been converted into a digital format by the streaming provider. In actual fact it has already been cleaned. Before everything else you need to check that the microphone settings are suitable for the sound type you want. And remember to deploy all available software-based methods for reducing occasional extraneous noises during the recording process….
Sound Forge Audio Cleaning Lab comes with several handy functions for cleaning old recordings. It is even possible to remove noise from centre-filled records - i.e. with two stereo sound tracks of identical length - because the generated signal comes from inside the record and you can remove it. <|begin_of_text|>In the market for a low-cost networked storage solution? You may want to take a look at the Netgear ReadyNAS 104.
Typically, home users have been subjected to very few, true performance NAS products. If you wanted true performance (i.e. at least an ISO 3.0 write speeds and an ISO 4.0 read speeds), you basically had to accept a very high price tag for the product. However, times have changed with vendors realizing that more users need more centralized storage with throughput for handling a higher number of users.
Prior to the release of the CPU/SSD/NVMe-based products, NAS vendors concentrated on RAID 6 before introducing RAID 10. This never accomplished performance as much as it did data protection. Today, things have changed with vendors offering RAID 01, RAID 5 and RAID 6 on their higher performance products. This allows users to balance performance with data redundancy. Even vendors such as Asus, Synology, QNAP, and Netgear include NVM Express and CPU-based storage products for powerhouse performance, with model lines such as the RT-AX86U, SRM-3202+, TS-251D, and ReadyNAS 422. As an example, Western Digital offers a few of these types of higher performance solutions designed around RMT, or RAID Massively Parallel Technology. It lowers RAID latency and improves performance, increases scalability, and enhances reliability. Ultimately, dramatically accelerating throughput.
Today, we talk with a company that understands these higher performance concepts. The Netgear ReadyNAS series has been on the market for several years. And during this time, Netgear has gradually expanded the performance aspect of the ReadyNAS line. Initially, a majority of models were based on RAID 2 and RAID 1. As the line matured, Netgear introduced RAID 0 and higher performance models that allowed for RAID 5 and RAID 6. <|begin_of_text|>Gloria Williams Sander is hoping that her home in Glendale’s North Cumberland Heights neighborhood soon will become a historical district.
With her neighbor Susan Dasso and others, Williams Sander canvassed the neighborhood a few years ago to learn if any residents would be willing to support an inclusionary district, and she reported that unanimous support emerged.
“There was no one against it,” she said.
Williams Sander was among area leaders, including Glendale Mayor Dave Weaver, who were honored for their efforts toward fostering community gardens at a ceremony on Saturday. But perhaps more important to her was being recognized alongside her son Chris Sander, a horticulturist with the city of Glendale, for their enthusiasms in gardening.
“I couldn’t do it without my son,” she said.
For his part, Sander said that his mother got him interested in gardening.
At their home, Williams Sander has long taken many opportunities to add greenery, developing their front and backyard. John Bradford has earned national recognition for his N. Cumberland Heights neighborhood garden in Glendale that includes hens. Lori Gray James photos
“To her, there was no gardening, there was no lawn,” he said of his mother. “I got my green thumb for her.”
A former mayor of Glendale and a one-term council member for the city of Peoria, Williams Sander brought a strong practical streak to civic issues, and she similarly emphasizes pragmatic methods in her approach to gardening.
She said she likes to “[take] what [others] don’t want… and do something with it.”
In her eyes, permaculture — an ethical design methodology that targets sustainability and balance — affords a strong conceptual foundation for her pursuits. She likes to describe permaculture as “designing ecosystems for human good.”
Williams Sander’s drawn from the practice to accentuate plants that give different results depending on the season. As an example, she said that particular flowers yield early in the spring and summer, and then return after they fade. Afterward, the same flowers attract butterflies and caterpillars during the fall.
Other elements include adornments sprouting from the ground and not from above, to show a visual transition. Williams Sander also likes continuity, as well as to work with plants striving for food products and those offering vivid colors.
Her front yard includes sand-misty yellow roses; its occasional plum tree bears lecianthus….

The third blog with an online petition was run by Nguyen Chi Tuyen in Ho Chi Minh City.

Fuemmeler said Azzato was traveling at speeds anywhere from five to 10 miles per hour.
His dog, named Rafe, was found running loose about a half-mile away.

<|begin_of_text|>Australian internet users were the big losers from today's NBN Co deal with Telstra, according to opposition communications spokesman Malcolm Turnbull, as it condemns them to pay high broadband prices.
The $11 billion deal with Telstra paved the way for non-blocking NBN Co connections and an $11 billion company deposit to Telstra has also now been set up where the telco money could be diverted to in this form, according to Turnbull.
This amounts to "a $1,000 surcharge on every computer on the internet for every year it operates on the network", said Turnbull who declared that he was "concerned".
He also warned Australia would probably face another 3 years of promised 25Mbps speeds never being realised.
Minister for Broadband, Communications and the Digital Economy Stephen Conroy refrained from calling Turnbull a chicken little when he responded to the opposition spokesman’s assertions. This NBN Company Deposit is effectively "a $25 cheque, we are writing to the Telstra Board while the deal is being finalised", Conroy said later in the day.
The NBN model is missing a crucial ingredient: competition, Conroy alleged. 99.98% of Australians will get a fibre to the node network, delivered by around 100 commercial retailers. Strong competition will deliver higher speeds faster. Under the failed Coalition model, there will still be no choice and no competition after the expenditure of $43 billion, said Conroy. This dramatically undermined Turnbull's assertions that Australians would now have a choice of NBN pipes — he gave this claim in early November.
Turnbull Monday railed on the simplicity of the NBN Co Telstra deal. Home-based Telstra customers won't need to change ISPs. Those residential Telstra customers, receiving NBN speeds of downstream upto 100Mbps, get these speeds drawn from the near-ready HFC cable network that would have cost around $3.5 billion just to build or which is far less cost than what Telstra is claiming.
Today's news of the $11 billion Telstra cash infusion adds to the already healthy NBN co balance sheet and further undercuts more fees paid by Telstra to not come onto the NBN access network.
Today's Telstra-fortune-distributing $11 billion company deposit could possibly resemble the $100 million contingent consideration paid to Deutsche Telekom for its US joint venture with Verizon, suggested Conroy today. Telstra…should use the value of that deposit to its shareholders and assist its competitors to build their national broadband networks, declared Conroy.

<|begin_of_text|>Fisher-Price issued a recall of 4.7 million Rock ‘n Play Sleepers Friday after multiple infants were found to have died while the product was in use.
According to the Consumer Product Safety Division’s website, 30 infant fatalities have been confirmed where infants ages 3 months or older had used unsupported, inclined sleep products, like the Fisher-Price Rock ‘n Play. In many of these cases, the infant had fallen asleep in the product, with the head propped up by the inclined sleeping surface.
“Our hearts are with the families who have lost their loved ones as a result.”
In April of this year, the CPSF division labeled all inclined sleepers unsafe with this warning on its website: “Improper use of sleep products, including inclined sleep products like the Rock ‘n Play Sleeper, can cause infants to experience breathing or suffocation problems and increase the risk of SIDS.”
4.7 million units of the Rock ‘n Play Sleeper are included in the recall, which originated in 2009. The sleeper is still available for purchase at Walmart with model numbers RNORP314 or RNORP314W. Anyone who has purchased the product can visit Fisher-Price’s website to receive a refund.
The Rock ‘n Play Sleeper is a portable infant crib with an inclined surface that allows parents to place infants as young as 3 months in it, as opposed to a traditional flat crib surface. The concept behind inclined sleeping is that infants would be able to sleep at an angle similar to how they slept in the womb, making the process more comfortable. Manufacturers of the sleepers believe that this minimalist approach to crib design would provide infants with a safer sleeping environment.
The Rock ‘n Play Sleeper comes with two settings–flat and upright–and has been approved by the Consumer Product Safety Commission since its production began.

<|begin_of_text|>Unprecedented back-to-back annual coral bleaching events have affected two-thirds of the Great Barrier Reef, with this year's event already leading to mortality of half the corals in some key tourist tracts, scientists say.
Record-breaking warm waters along Australia's northeast coast during 2014-15 laid waste to some sections of the reef, with the spectacle Australia's worst ever mass bleaching event.
In this year's first major climate-related event to blight the reef, ocean temperatures have again climbed toward record highs, leaving coral communities across the Great Barrier Reef extremely susceptible to a repeat.
Coral bleaching happens when fragile polyps -- the microscopic animals that form the building blocks of coral colonies -- abandon their symbiotic relationship with microscopic algae called zooxanthellae responsible for keeping coral healthy.
A shift toward cool ocean waters early this year allowed coral communities to bounce back from severe loss. Warmer waters from April have many scientists concerned, forecasting another widespread bleaching event.
NASA satellite data calculated the extent of coral loss and found 93% of southern areas bleached moderately, severely with an unprecedented 1.68 million hectares of corals suffering bleaching.
Bleached coral can fight back by recolonizing with algae, but there is a fine line between bleaching from the hottest water temps to infertile death, with average temperatures going up in the reef chances are the coral will now die.
These back-to-back mass bleaching events dramatically change water temperatures, which bleached corals can't cope with and coral is unlikely able to survive in hostile ocean conditions.
Scientists Monday released the devastating results of this year's bleaching event across the world's largest coral reef system in north-east Australia.
Interim results from a comprehensive aerial survey by The University of Queensland team revealed coral bleaching around the eighth of the marine park near Rockhampton in the Capricorn Bunker Group and around Green Island just north of Cairns.
"A massive early curtain-raiser from climate change," James Kerry from CSIRO said.
This year, far north and northwestern sections of the reef show low to moderate bleaching triggered by ocean temperatures a few degrees above normal.
"This shows how variable ocean temperatures can be even in a single year and how difficult it is to predict coral bleaching patterns," JK Perry of James Cook University said.
"The north was spared...centered primarily on far-southern reefs," Ben Lau of the Australian Institute of Marine Science (AIMS) said of this year's bleaching event.
The southern bleaching is similar to the 2011 event, with AIMS monitoring many of the reefs that will recover within months, particularly inside the marine park.

When I was in my 20s and early 30s, I used to work nonstop and play tennis in the late evenings to calm my nerves.
On Jan. 1, 2008, I resolved to start playing tennis in the early mornings. Ten years later, I’ve kept that resolution more than 95 percent of the time. The morning matches are always well-attended by a set of friends who are all in their 40s and 50s. I can’t lie: The mental impact on those who never accomplished much as children begins to fade when we compete. And as we age, our bodies need to be strong to feel entitled to play at all.
Tennis is very unique in that whoever is the worst player or least likely to win, we are all still enjoying the match. And the player who is the best, often reflecting on his or her past struggles, is with us in spirit, providing the advice and inspiration we sorely need—as Roger Federer recently did in Seattle—and saying, “Yes, this is what you need to do.” We need to learn the true meaning of sportsmanship.
The Me Generation is starting to fade; now we are starting to recognize and embrace the fact that there is power and strength in a team. We all are doing this for one another; for the great cause of fighting Parkinson’s disease; and, equally important, to have some fun.
May is Parkinson’s Awareness Month, and we are having our annual dinner—helping to get the word out on what a disease that is growing, but not known by many—who get hit hard by it—in eighth, ninth and 10th graders in high school.
We need to get the word out again just how prevalent this disease is. When we moved to LA from Seattle in 1992 we discovered that Parkinson’s was bigger than we thought and that once you had it, it controlled everything you did—and how long you would live.
And what we come to learn is that you must live life to the fullest. Limiting what you can do is practically moot and striving to accomplish the seemingly impossible is the only way to get better. There is far too much energy and time wasted on thinking what you can’t do.
Our main responsibility, and our best attempt at battling Parkinson’s, is to take control and find new ways to keep our minds and bodies going strong.

Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions. You can minimize distractions from competitors, hecklers at cross-country meets or even your own internal doubts by developing your focus.
Why Do I Need to Stay Focused?
While many people run for the exercise, fun and social aspects of the sport, when you are competing in races or devoted to improving your time, it is important to stay focused. Being focused has a direct correlation with your performance. When you stay focused, you can probably improve your time by kilometers per day because you aren't as scatterbrained during your run and because you don't have as many distractions -- and distractions can lead to injury.
To build a solid running foundation, you have to develop mental strength. These tips can help you take your mental presence to the next level so that you can continue to improve your running performances. Remember too, that reflecting on your performance while you run can be a great source of enrichment and self-knowledge, akin to journals you might keep.
